## Executive TL;DR: The Immediate Root Risk

**Objective:**  
To validate the security posture of the Ignite VM (IP: 10.64.152.244) focusing on vectors leading to full administrative system compromise and data exfiltration.

**Executive Summary (Critical):**  
The assessment exposed a fundamentally broken security control within the web application: **Unauthenticated Local File Inclusion (LFI)**.  
ðŸ”— LFI (OWASP): https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal

This LFI was immediately leveraged to achieve **Remote Code Execution (RCE)**.  
ðŸ”— RCE (OWASP): https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Code_Injection

Critically, the web application failed the **Principle of Least Privilege** by running with the Root account's privileges.  
ðŸ”— Least Privilege Reference: https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control

This eliminated the need for Privilege Escalation (PrivEsc).  
The entire breach, from initial reconnaissance to verified Root access, was executed in under 45 minutes, demonstrating an unacceptable time-to-compromise.

**Immediate Business Risk:**  
ðŸš¨ **CATASTROPHIC AND IMMINENT.**  
This attack chain means a hostile actor can breach the network perimeter, seize full control of the hosting server, deploy ransomware, steal all stored data, and use this host as a staging ground for a lateral attack against your entire internal network. Immediate containment (P0 actions) is not optional.

**Status:**  
Full Root compromise verified. Findings validated and documented across 15 verifiable forensic steps.

