## Detailed Vulnerability Analysis: The Attack Path

### WEB-01 â€” Unauthenticated LFI \rightarrow RCE (CRITICAL - P0)

Description: The application's file handling mechanism, likely in the /ignite/ path, implicitly trusts unvalidated user input via a URL parameter. This weakness permits Local File Inclusion (LFI), allowing the reading of sensitive system files (e.g., /etc/passwd). The exploit was upgraded to Remote Code Execution (RCE) by exploiting file path injection combined with server logging or environment variables. This is the single point-of-failure for network security.

Impact (The Fear Factor): This is the equivalent of leaving the server's brain exposed to the internet. An attacker can remotely inject and execute arbitrary system commands, effectively transforming your hosting server into a drone controlled by the attacker, granting Initial Access effortlessly.

Lab PoC Highlights (See ðŸ“¸ 7 & ðŸ“¸ 8): The use of a simple cat /etc/passwd LFI test, followed by command injection (such as a Log Poisoning or Shellshock vector), confirmed RCE capability instantaneously, proving no complex techniques are required.

Jira Ticket: SEC-RCE-002 â€” CRITICAL: IMMEDIATE â€” Enforce strict server-side Whitelisting for all file parameters. Immediately disable the interpretation of special characters (../, wrappers) and hardcode file paths.

### SYS-01 â€” Web Application Running as Root User (CRITICAL - P0)

Description: The post-exploitation analysis revealed the single most devastating configuration flaw: The application process being compromised (via WEB-01) was running with the privileges of the Root account. This is a severe violation of the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP).

Impact (System Takeover): This flaw constitutes an unauthenticated, non-traceable, straight-line path to full administrative control. Since the initial web shell already runs as Root, the attacker has achieved total system dominance from the very first shell, enabling kernel-level persistence and complete data control without the need for a separate PrivEsc phase.

Lab PoC Highlights (See ðŸ“¸ 10): The command whoami executed via the RCE channel returned the expected result: root. This ease of execution dramatically elevates the risk score to the highest possible level.

Jira Ticket: SEC-POLP-001 â€” IMMEDIATE â€” Reconfigure the web server (Apache/Nginx/Ignition) to run with a dedicated, unprivileged service account (e.g., www-data). NEVER run public-facing services as Root.

