## Technical Proof & Screenshots (15 Step-by-Step Evidence)

> WARNING: These 15 steps represent the verifiable, forensic evidence of the attack. Every step confirms a security failure. Raw logs and unredacted screenshots are included in the NDA delivery package.

### Screenshot Evidence

All screenshots and raw logs are available in the repository under /screenshots/ and /logs/ respectively.

> Sensitive values (IP addresses, flags, session tokens) have been redacted in public copies â€” full artifacts are available on request under NDA.

* **Nmap Full Scan (SS01)**  
  * Description: Full Nmap scan showing open ports and service fingerprints.  
  * Notes: Command used: nmap -sC -sV -p- `<target>`

* **Gobuster Directory Scan (SS02)**  
  * Description: Directory enumeration results showing discovered paths, including the key application path.  
  * Notes: Wordlist used: common.txt

* **Website Homepage (SS03)**  
  * Description: Default homepage of the target web server, identifying the application type.  
  * Notes: Helps identify framework or CMS.

* **Identifying Vulnerable Parameter (SS04)**  
  * Description: Discovery of the LFI-vulnerable URL parameter via inspection or testing.  
  * Notes: Vulnerable parameter sanitized.

* **LFI Test: Reading /etc/passwd (SS05)**  
  * Description: Attempting a path traversal attack to read a known sensitive file.  
  * Notes: Payload: ../../../etc/passwd

* **LFI Success (SS06)**  
  * Description: Successful LFI confirmed by viewing the system user database.  
  * Notes: User accounts redacted.

* **Preparing RCE Payload (SS07)**  
  * Description: Preparing the custom command injection payload leveraging the LFI path.  
  * Notes: Shows Netcat listening on port 80 or 22 for log injection.

* **RCE Command Execution Request (SS08)**  
  * Description: Execution of the crafted LFI payload to trigger RCE via the vulnerable parameter.  
  * Notes: Access path partially sanitized.

* **RCE Confirmation (Initial) (SS09)**  
  * Description: Arbitrary command execution successfully verified via web output.  
  * Notes: Shows compromised server response.

* **Root Access Confirmation (SS10)**  
  * Description: CRITICAL FINDING: Confirming the compromised user is the highest privileged user: root.  
  * Notes: Privilege Escalation NOT Required.

* **Root Directory Enumeration (SS11)**  
  * Description: Listing the contents of the /root/ directory to locate the final flag.  
  * Notes: Directory contents sanitized.

* **Retrieving user.txt Flag (SS12)**  
  * Description: Retrieved user flag from compromised machine.  
  * Notes: Flag redacted.

* **Retrieving root.txt Flag (SS13)**  
  * Description: Retrieved root flag after confirming system dominance.  
  * Notes: Sensitive parts hidden.

* **System Information Capture (SS14)**  
  * Description: Capturing operating system and kernel information for forensic documentation.  
  * Notes: Hostnames and OS versions redacted.

* **Post-Compromise Cleanup (SS15)**  
  * Description: Final action: Simulating an attacker attempting to cover their tracks by deleting log entries.  
  * Notes: Shows commands like rm /tmp/shell.php or log file manipulation.

